At least 23 people, mostly children, became ill with a serious and rare bacterial infection after swimming in a pool at the Best Western Plus hotel in Brunswick in March 2023, a lawsuit filed in Cumberland County Superior Court last week alleges.

The case involves two groups that swam at the Best Western pool on two separate occasions between March 3-5, 2023: one group was at the hotel for a hockey tournament and the other for a children’s birthday party.

The 15 plaintiffs in the case claim that the owners of the hotel, Giri Hotel Management and Giri Brunswick, had been cited for health violations more than a year before the plaintiffs became ill, but did not address the violations. In the time between the health inspection in January 2022 and the families falling ill in March 2023, the complaint filed by Garmey Law in Portland states that the hotel continued to allow guests to use its pool.

These violations included those labeled “critical” under Maine law — which are required to be remediated within 10 days — such as failing to have a certified pool operator, failing to have a functioning disinfectant feeder, not completing required chlorine testing and recordkeeping and failing to follow operational safety rules.

In the hours and days following their time in the pool, all of the plaintiffs, including some adults, contracted a bacterial infection known as pseudomonas aeruginosa, or p. aeruginosa, according to the lawsuit. It alleges that parents complained to the hotel but were told their illness was not caused by the pool.

Inspectors returned in March 2023 after the families reported their illnesses. The state declared the pool an “imminent health hazard” and ordered it closed. By that time, the health inspector was not able to test for p. aeruginosa because hotel management had already dumped chlorine in the pool, the complaint says.

