P. aeruginosa is a serious and sometimes drug-resistant infection that resulted in 2,700 deaths in the U.S. in 2017, according to the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. It can cause a wide range of symptoms, including rashes, infections in the eyes, blood, skin, lungs and ears, itchiness and swelling, flu-like symptoms and more. The plaintiffs were ill for weeks or months after the exposure, their lawyers said.

The Maine Center for Disease Control and Prevention and the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention classified the incident as an outbreak, writing in a January 2024 [report](https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/73/wr/mm7302a2.htm#F1_down) that inadequate maintenance and monitoring of chlorine concentration in the hotel pool was the most likely cause. Among those who entered the pool in the days in question and responded to questions by the CDC, 88% became ill.

[Giri Hotel Management](https://girihotels.com/portfolio/), based in Quincy, Massachusetts, owns several other hotels in Maine, including Anchorage by the Sea in Ogunquit, Harraseeket Inn in Freeport, and the Hilton Garden Inn and Fairfield Inn near the Portland Jetport, according to the company’s website. The Best Western in the Brunswick case is at 71 Gurnet Road in the Cook’s Corner neighborhood.

The management company did not immediately respond to an emailed request for comment Friday.

“When companies ignore laws and regulations designed to protect the public, and  
especially children, the harm is not abstract,” attorney Peter Richard of Garmey Law wrote in a news release. “The risk taken by the Defendant Giri Hotels with the public’s health and with the wellbeing of its hotel guests shocks the conscience. The conscious risks taken with the public’s health finally caught up with the Defendant, manifesting itself in an easily preventable outbreak of an infectious disease that injured innocent children and guests of the hotel.”

